            It was considered that it would be too prescriptive for the details of the relationship between principal regulators and the Charity Commission to be expressly set out on the face of the Bill. It is intended to establish a committee of principal regulators to share best practice and to ensure consistent communication and
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_408gc' title='Col. 408GC &mdash; HL Deb 14 March 2005 vol 670 c408GC' name='column_408gc' href='#column_408gc' rel='bookmark'>408GC</a>
            application of regulatory requirements. We all want to try to keep bureaucracy to a minimum. I am not sure that this amendment fits that bill. I hope that the noble Lord will withdraw it with good grace.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0670P0-04799'>
